The {{glossary|noun}} is derived from {{compound|en|scare|t1=to frighten, startle, terrify|crow|t2=bird of the genus ''Corvus''}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=172022|date=September 2022}}</ref><ref>{{R:Dictionary.com|pos=n|source=Random House}}</ref> The word displaced other terms such as {{m|en|bogle}} {{qualifier|now dialectal|dated}}, {{m|en|sewel}} or {{m|en|shewel}}, and {{m|en|shoy-hoy}} (perhaps imitative of the cry of crows).

The {{glossary|verb}} is derived from the noun.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=v|id=172023|date=March 2022}}</ref>

